<FIRST>u a AM-EarthDayRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0604 04-23 0792</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earth Day Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0604,0812</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmentalists Mark Earth Day With Worldwide Demonstrations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 12th graf, `Near Wichita ...' to UPDATE with lower police
estimate of crowd. INSERTS 3 grafs after 16th graf, `The weather ...' to
UPDATE with Michigan, San Jose events; picks up 17th graf, `About 200 ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people from Budapest, Hungary, to Wichita, Kansas
marked the 20th annual Earth Day on Saturday with protests against
the Exxon tanker spill, ozone-destroying chemicals and other
environmental concerns.
   But demonstrations fizzled in Sweden and India for lack of
interest, and a rally in West Germany attracted less than 100
people, officials said.
   In New York City, about 1,000 demonstrators rallied at Exxon's
midtown headquarters, then marched to the United Nations.
Organizers estimated the crowd swelled to more than 5,000 people by
the end of the march, but police put the number at 2,500.
   The Exxon tanker Exxon Valdez ran aground near Valdez, Alaska,
on March 24, spilling 10.1 million gallons of crude oil into
wildlife-rich Prince William Sound in the worst such spill in
American history.
   In a speech to demonstrators, activist Jeremy Rifkin said
environmental politics had changed dramatically since the first
Earth Day in 1970.
   ``All of our previous environmental crises have been regional in
nature. Now we are experiencing for the first time a global
environmental crisis,'' Rifkin said. ``The greenhouse effect,
global warming, ozone depletion, acid rain and species extinction
now threaten the entire planet and all the inhabitants that live in
it.
   ``This is the first international Earth Day,'' he said, claiming
it was the first time demonstrations were coordinated around the
world.
   In Rome, about 1,000 people and 40 environmentalists cheered as
20 protesters dressed in cardboard costumes resembling aerosol cans
and refrigerators ran up the Spanish Steps and smashed through a
paper hoop symbolizing the Earth's ozone layer.
   The demonstration was intended to re-enact the creation of holes
in the ozone layer by chlorofluorocarbons, which are chemicals used
in aerosol propellants and refrigerators.
   Ozone occurs naturally in the Earth's stratosphere and screens
out harmful ultraviolet light from the sun. Studies have shown that
chlorofluorocarbons are breaking down the protective barrier.
   In Budapest's Vorosmarty Square, several hundred people turned
out for a demonstration sponsored by the Radical Party.
Demonstrators included Ilona ``Cicciolina'' Staller, a
Hungarian-born porn actress and a Radical Party member of Italy's
parliament, and Nobel Prize-winning biophysicist Maurice H. F.
Wilkins of Britain.
   Near Wichita, Kan., about 750 people gathered outside chemical
plants owned by Racon Inc. and Vulcan Chemicals to demand they stop
using chlorofluorocarbons within a year.
   According to environmentalists, Racon is one of five U.S.
companies that produce the chemicals and Vulcan is major supplier
to those businesses.
   Spokesmen for the two companies said a ban on
chlorofluorocarbons is not realistic because reliable alternatives
have not been found, and that the chemical industry is spending
billions of dollars trying to find other substances.
   In Frankfurt, West Germany, only about 60 people turned out for
a demonstration at the Hoechst chemical company, police said.
   ``The weather was pretty rainy, and that might have had
something to do with it,'' said police spokesman Wolfgang Nebelung.
   About 500 people rallied at a park in San Jose, Calif., and
marched to an IBM plant where they tied green and white ribbons on
a gate to protest the use of chlorofluorocarbons in the electronics
industry.
   ``In this beautiful setting we are dealing with a problem that
in 20 years could be deadly. In 20 years, it may not be safe for
people to lie in the sun,'' consumer advocate Ralph Nader said at
the rally.
   More than 1,000 people learned how to make non-toxic household
cleaners and received other environmental tips at an exposition at
Michigan State University in East Lansing.
   About 200 people gathered in Chicago for an Earth Day observance
that resembled a picnic more than a protest.
   Speakers, however, criticized Exxon for its part in the oil
spill. ``This would not be a safe place for a person from Exxon,''
said Bob Rudner of Greenpeace.
   Bill Harding showed up in a bathrobe made of common lawn grass,
and hawked grow-your-own starter kits for $25 each.
   ``It makes me feel closer to the Earth,'' Harding said. ``It's
like you have your own portable environment.''
   In Harrisburg, Pa., Gov. Robert Casey marked Earth Day by
announcing more than $600,000 in grants for cleaning up the
Susquehanna River Valley.
   Environmentalists at the University of Colorado in Boulder
celebrated Earth Day on Friday with a Festival of the Earth
featured a recycling Olympics in which competitors stomped aluminum
cans and rolled trash bins in relay races.
   The first Earth Day celebration was held in April 1970.
</TEXT>
