<FIRST>r a AM-SkinheadGathering 2ndLd-Writethru a0599 04-23 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Skinhead Gathering, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0599,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foes of Racism March to Protest Neo-Nazi Conference</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `Police worked ... with 2 grafs to UPDATE with
cross burning; picks up 3rd graf, `The 500 ...' SUBS 11th graf, `Sheriff's
deputies ...' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with details; picks up 12th graf,
`We've established ...' SUBS grafs 14-15, `Thirty to ... supremacist movement'
with 1 graf to conform; picks up 16th graf, `The anti-racism ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN K. WILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COEUR D'ALENE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of anti-racism
demonstrators marched for seven miles along a highway Saturday to
protest a gathering of skinheads and neo-Nazis nearby.
   After dark, the leader of the white supremacists was heard
leading a cross-burning ceremony and a glow was visible to
reporters a half-mile away.
   Police worked throughout the day to head off any confrontations
between the two groups.
   The 500 mostly young demonstrators on the Walk For Racial
Equality carried banners that proclaimed ``Celebrate Diversity''
and ``No Aryan Homeland in Our Home.''
   ``We're trying to show the rest of the country that Idaho is not
just potatoes and Nazis,'' said Russ Gee, a 26-year-old who was
among a contingent of people from the University of Idaho.
   A phalanx of Idaho State Police and Kootenai County sheriff's
patrol cars screened the marchers as they walked down a paved
bicycle path alongside the northern Idaho highway. A police
helicopter hovered overhead.
   The potential for violence and an unwillingness to give
publicity to the white supremacists led some human rights groups to
boycott the march, which ended two miles from the Aryan Nations
compound where a three-day conference of neo-Nazis and skinheads is
being held.
   Up to 2,000 anti-racism marchers had been expected, but
organizers said the opposition by some groups and cloudy, 47-degree
weather may have kept the numbers down.
   The marchers came from throughout the Pacific Northwest and
represented such groups as gay and lesbian activists, the
Washington state Rainbow Coalition and People Opposed to South
African Apartheid.
   Meanwhile, about two dozen participants in the white supremacist
gathering goose-stepped down the 200-foot road leading to their
compound to meet with reporters. Earlier, they canceled a march of
their own, saying skinheads did not want to be exposed to the
demonstrators.
   Kim A. Badynski, the Northwest organizer for the Ku Klux Klan,
said a cross would be burned there Saturday night.
   Reporters were kept a half-mile away from the gathering at the
30-acre ranch of Richard Butler, whose Aryan Nations group wants to
turn the Northwest into a ``whites only'' homeland. But Butler
could be heard leading a cross-burning ceremony after dark and a
glow was seen coming from the ranch.
   Sheriff's deputies had set up checkpoints on roads leading to
the Aryan Nations camp near Hayden Lake to check the IDs of people
entering the area.
   ``We've established what we feel to be tactics that are going to
ensure the safety of all the parties involved,'' said sheriff's
Capt. Tom Dickson.
   Lisa Anderson, organizer of Citizens for Nonviolent Action
Against Racism, the Coeur d'Alene group sponsoring the march, said
she expected few problems.
   Thirty to 40 Neo-Nazi youths were staying at Butler's ranch.
Butler said white supremacist leaders, including Ku Klux Klansmen,
would hold workshops on the white supremacist movement.
   The anti-racism march was endorsed by Jesse Jackson's Rainbow
Coalition and Washington Gov. Booth Gardner, but groups such as the
Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith stayed away.
   Marvin Stern, regional ADL director in Seattle, said his group
``views with great concern the events surrounding this weekend's
planned conference'' but decided not to march because of the burden
on law enforcement and potential for violence.
   Gov. Cecil Andrus also refused to endorse the march, echoing
fears that it could promote violence and give white supremacists
more publicity.
   The ADL estimates there are 2,500 to 3,000 neo-Nazi skinheads in
30 states, an increase in both numbers and geography since a 1988
report, Stern said.
   Many skinhead organizations do not espouse neo-Nazi beliefs, but
the conference demonstrates right-wing leaders' attempts to recruit
them, he said.
</TEXT>
