<FIRST>r a BC-Pakistan     04-23 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Pakistan,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Pakistan Ordered Afghan Rebel Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An assault by guerrillas on a key Afghan town
was ordered by the Pakistani government at a meeting attended by
the U.S. ambassador to Pakistan, The New York Times reported in its
Sunday editions.
   The attack on the town, Jalalabad, was ordered against the
advice of the Pakistani director of military intelligence, the
newspaper reported, citing a Pakistani participant in the meeting
and other Pakistani officials.
   There was no Afghan present on March 5 when the decision was
made, the Times said.
   The Times reported that U.S. Ambassador Robert B. Oakley
attended the meeting but that it could not learn whether he took
part in the discussion or decision. Oakley, contacted by The
Associated Press in Islamabad on Sunday morning, refused to comment.
   State Department spokeswoman Sondra McCarty, asked to comment on
the newspaper's report Saturday night, said, ``I don't have
anything on that.''
   Afghan guerrillas laid siege to Jalalabad two days after the
meeting, and the offensive now is mired in its seventh week.
   Pakistani and U.S. officials had predicted that the Moslem
guerrillas would quickly overthrow the Soviet-backed Afghan
government after the Soviets finished withdrawing their troops on
Feb. 15.
   Pakistani Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto's government ordered the
attack with the belief that an impressive victory in the town would
enhance the rebels' chances of forging ahead to the Afghan capital,
Kabul, the Times said.
   The newspaper reported that a participant in the March 5 meeting
said that Lt. Gen. Hamid Gul, director of Pakistan's intelligence
agency, opposed the assault, saying that the rebels were not
capable of launching a conventional warfare attack to capture the
town.
   But a close adviser to Bhutto, retired Maj. Gen. Nasirullah
Babar, said that too much time had passed without a major rebel
victory since Soviet Union troop withdrawal was completed,
according to the Times.
   Since the Soviet intervention in Afghanistan in 1979, the
Pakistani Directorate General for Inter Services Intelligence, a
branch of the military, has shaped the guerrilla alliance and
coordinated its actions, the Times reported.
   When the United States threw its support behind the rebels, the
Central Intelligence Agency became Pakistan's main partner, the
newspaper said.
</TEXT>
