<FIRST>r i AM-Pope-Beatifications     04-23 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope-Beatifications,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Beatifies Two Spanish Priests, Three Nuns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Sunday beatified two
Spanish missionaries, who were martyred in 17th-century Japan, and
three nuns who founded religious orders or did charity work abroad.
   The five made blesseds of the Roman Catholic Church were the
Rev. Martino di San Nicola; the Rev. Melchiorre di Sant'Agostino;
Sister Francesca Siedliska, a 19th century Polish nun; Sister Maria
Caterina di Santo Agostino, a 17th century French nun; and Sister
Maria Margherita Caiani, a 19th century Italian nun.
   Beatification is a step toward possible sainthood.
   The two Spanish missionaries were burned to death in 1632 over a
fire made with wet straw and green wood to keep it from burning too
quickly. They were tied by only a finger so they could break free
and demonstrate they were abandoning Christianity. Instead, the two
priests died for their faith.
   Sister Siedliska founded the Congregation of the Sacred Family
of Nazareth and Sister Caiani founded the Little Franciscan Sisters
of the Sacred Heart. Sister Agostino was beatified for her work in
Canada with the sick, poor and elderly.
</TEXT>
