<UNK>Protesters Demonstrate Against Proposed Nuclear Plant</UNK>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,000 demonstrators marched through
Taipei streets Sunday to protest the proposed building of Taiwan's
fourth nuclear power plant.
   The demonstrators began the four-hour protest in heavy rain
outside a memorial hall in downtown Taipei and marched a mile to
the Economics Ministry, which supervises state-run companies.
   The march ended peacefully after ministry officials accepted a
letter of protest from demonstrators.
   ``We don't want another nuclear power plant. There are no fish
in the sea near the three nuclear power plants because of nuclear
waste pollution,'' said protester Wu Tien-fu, an 82-year-old
fisherman.
   Most demonstrators were residents of Yenliao village in Taipei
County, where the state-run Taiwan Power Co. announced in 1986 it
would build the $7.4 billion plant.
   Earlier Sunday, protest leaders delivered a petition, signed by
2,565 households of Yenliao village, that urged President Lee
Teng-hui to scrap the plant.
