<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Takeshita     04-23 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Takeshita,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters March at Prime Minister's Home to Demand That He Quit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 60 neighbors of Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita marched to his home Sunday, demanding that he abolish a
new 3 percent sales tax and then resign.
   The group, which included parents with their children, marched
2.5 miles and stopped about 50 yards from Takeshita's home, said a
police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   He said the demonstration was organized by citizens' groups in
the Tokyo neighborhood.
   The Kyodo News Service said the marchers yelled anti-Takeshita
slogans while shop owners and other onlookers along the street
waved their hands in support.
   Kyodo said Chuji Shibuya, an organizer, read a statement
declaring: ``We are really angry at you (Takeshita). You must
immediately abolish the consumption tax ... and resign.''
   The tax was introduced April 1 as part of a tax reform package
that includes cuts in income taxes.
   Takeshita's governing Liberal Democratic Party forced the tax
package through Parliament last year over opposition objections.
   Meanwhile, the opposition and some members of Takeshita's own
party want him to resign because of his government's involvement in
a major stock-profiteering and bribery scandal.
   Recruit Co., an information services conglomerate, sold
bargain-priced unlisted shares in a subsidiary to about 160
influential government officials, politicians and businessmen. They
profited when the share prices rose after public sale began.
   So far, 14 people have been arrested, and three Cabinet
ministers have been forced to resign.
   Takeshita has acknowledged that he received more than $1 million
in contributions from Recruit and that an aide bought some of the
stock.
   But he has denied personal wrongdoing and vowed to stay in
office.
   In Kyodo's latest poll, support for Takeshita fell below 4
percent.
</TEXT>
