<HEAD>Leftist Party Opposes Bush Visit To West Berlin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leftist political party in West Berlin's
coalition government said Sunday that protests will result if
President Bush accepts the mayor's invitation to visit this divided
city.
   ``We can do without a visit by Bush,'' said Hilde Schramm, a
parliamentary member of the Alternative List Party. Ms. Schramm
told The Associated Press the Alternative List strongly opposes
Bush's stand on a number of issues.
   ``We do not like the policies of the United States in relation
to Nicaragua, its pressure (on Germany and other NATO members) to
modernize short-range nuclear weapons, and that it has not grasped
opportunities for disarmament,'' Ms. Schramm said.
   She said the Alternative List played no part in the decision
last week by West Berlin Mayor Walter Momper to invite Bush. She
said if Bush comes he will be met with demonstrations and that her
party will take part.
   There has been no announcement of whether Bush might travel to
Berlin.
   He visits West Germany next month, arriving in Bonn May 30 and
leaving the following day after talks with Chancellor Helmut Kohl
and other officials.
   Bush also plans to take a boat ride on the Rhine River, but
there are no plans for a trip to West Berlin, diplomatic sources
say.
   The Alternative List is the junior partner in the coalition
government led by Momper's mainstream Social Democrats. The union
resulted from the election defeat of the governing Christian
Democrats in January.
   It has been an uneasy political marriage because of the
Alternative List's often far-left views on key matters.
   The Alternative List and its sister party, the Greens, have in
the past helped stage huge anti-U.S. demonstrations.
