<FIRST>r i AM-Zimbabwe-Funeral     04-23 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zimbabwe-Funeral,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corruption-Linked Ex-Minister Given Hero's Funeral</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN EDLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Zimbabwean politician who
committed suicide after quitting the Cabinet in a corruption
scandal was buried Sunday as a national hero.
   Thousands flocked to Heroes' Acre, a shrine to those who died in
the independence war, for the state funeral of Maurice Nyagumbo. He
was the senior political affairs minister until resigning this
month.
   President Robert Mugabe paid tribute to the politician, who was
among his closest aides.
   Mugabe described Nyagumbo as a ``gallant freedom fighter'' and
``an outstanding revolutionary'' who made many sacrifices to
liberate his homeland from British colonial rule.
   The president told mourners Nyagumbo had taken his own life, and
police said he poisoned himself. The cause of death had been kept a
secret by authorities.
   Nyagumbo, 64, died in Harare's Parirenyatwa Hospital on Thursday
after being admitted with convulsions a day earlier.
   On Tuesday, Zimbabwe celebrated the ninth anniversary of its
independence from Britain, and the former minister was not invited
to the celebrations.
   Nyagumbo was one of the few surviving founders of Mugabe's
ruling Zimbabwe African National Union, the party that waged a
seven-year guerrilla war for independence.
   He spent two decades in colonial prisons as an alleged terrorist
and was widely acclaimed by black Zimbabweans as a champion of
political emancipation.
   After independence he held key posts in the Cabinet, the
15-member Politburo and the governing Communist Party's central
committee.
   Nyagumbo resigned this month as Senior Minister for Political
Affairs and the party's administrative secretary after a
presidential inquiry found he was involved in a racket involving
the black-marketeering of vehicles.
   According to a report, Nyagumbo abused his position by arranging
for friends to buy 38 vehicles directly from a state assembly plant
instead of waiting like other would-be buyers for up to 10 years.
The report said Nyagumbo probably received financial rewards for
arranging the deals.
   The minister himself denied receiving kickbacks.
</TEXT>
