<FIRST>r i AM-SouthKorea     04-23 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Korea,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radical Students, Workers Clash With Riot Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INCHON, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police in two cities fired
volleys of tear gas and charged anti-government protesters Sunday
who tried to march from universities into the streets.
   Police and rifle squads armed with multiple tear gas launchers
fired scores of tear gas canisters at 600 demonstrating students
and workers, who hurled firebombs and rocks in the clash outside
Inchon University. Protesters burned an effigy of President Roh
Tae-woo and called for the overthrow of the government.
   ``Down with Roh Tae-woo who suppresses labor rights!''
protesters yelled in the port city about 30 miles west of Seoul.
   Riot police also used tear gas to disperse about 800 workers and
students who staged scattered street protests in the Songnam area
of southern Seoul.
   Protesters in Seoul took to the streets after attending the
funeral of a worker who burned himself to death April 3 in a labor
dispute. Workers and radical students sometimes commit ritual
suicide in South Korea as a form of protest.
   Protesters and police officers were hurt in both protests, but
police said there were no serious injuries and did not report any
arrests. The number of injured was not immediately available,
police said.
   Rally organizers had predicted thousands would attend the Inchon
rally, but the turnout was small.
   The rally came one day after 46 riot troopers were injured
storming a food factory held by striking workers in Inchon. The
strikers hurled diluted sulphuric acid and rocks at the police,
officials said. Five workers were injured and 38 were arrested in
Saturday's clash, they said.
   Militant labor groups have staged strikes around the nation to
demand higher wages and other concessions. The government has
warned the strikes are a serious threat to the national economy and
Roh said earlier this month that labor disputes had cost more than
$2 billion in lost production.
   Radical students have staged violent protests in support of
striking workers. They have little popular support and are not seen
as a major threat to the government.
</TEXT>
