<FIRST>r a AM-StephanSuit     04-23 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stephan Suit,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kansas Attorney General Popular Despite Personal Woes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEW FERGUSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Attorney General Robert T. Stephan
uses courts to fight crime, but a former employee has mired him for
6{ years in a court fight that cost him a shot at higher office,
contributed to the breakup of a marriage and sent him into
bankruptcy court.
   Stephan, a Republican serving his third four-year term, says he
may retire from public life, although his popularity remains high
and his personal problems do not appear to have hurt his
effectiveness.
   ``I'm going to persevere, but I've had about as much pain as
anyone in public office ever has,'' Stephan, 56, said in a recent
interview. ``God knows that those who inflicted that pain were not
justified in doing so.''
   ``If there is a hell, he's suffered it on Earth,'' said Rep. Dan
Glickman, a Democrat who is a friend of Stephan's.
   The case started in December 1982 when Marcia Tomson Stingley,
who had been fired from a clerk's job in his office, filed a
lawsuit accusing Stephan of sexual harassment. She accused him of
making lewd advances, crude remarks and suggestions of sexual
activity.
   Stephan denies her allegations, but agreed in March 1985 to
settle the lawsuit for $24,000 and other considerations, including
finding someone to buy her house and helping her get a job in
California.
   The settlement required that the terms be kept secret. But later
in that year, while Stephan considered a 1986 bid for governor,
rumors arose that Ms. Stingley had received state money. He
divulged that friends had raised the $24,000 from private sources,
and said he regretted having settled an ``unfounded and
ridiculous'' lawsuit.
   Ms. Stingley's attorney charged breach of contract for revealing
the settlement and threatened another suit unless Stephan paid her
$265,000. Stephan refused and the second suit was filed, knocking
him out of the governor's race, although he was re-elected attorney
general.
   The second case went to trial and a federal court jury last
November awarded $200,000 to Ms. Stingley, who is now 53.
   Stephan has appealed but couldn't afford to post the bond
required to block garnishment of his wages for the judgment. On
March 31, he filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy protection from
creditors, which prevented the withholding a fourth of his
$3,200-a-month take-home pay.
   Don Krueger, one of Ms. Stingley's attorneys, criticized Stephan
for avoiding the payment by the bankruptcy filing and said he
should resign.
   But Glickman defended Stephan's action, saying``he has a
perfectly justifiable right to use the bankruptcy court like any
other citizen does.''
   Ms. Stingley's daughter, Deborah Dempsey of San Diego, said her
mother will not comment on the case while the judgment is under
appeal.
   During the trial last fall, Ms. Stingley testified that Stephan
pushed her against a wall and asked her to have an affair with him.
She said she did nothing to encourage him.
   ``I told him I did not want this to occur. It was offensive to
me, it was demeaning,'' she said. Stephan made sexual advances
``numerous times,'' she said.
   Stephan, whose second wife divorced him during the litigation,
has married again and recently purchased a new home. He said his
financial problems might force him to look for other work in 1990
that would pay more than his state salary of $62,832.
   Politicians from both parties agree that Stephan would probably
have little trouble winning a fourth term if he seeks it.
   He has won praise for pushing legislation to guarantee certain
rights to crime victims, and has been a leading voice advocating
solution of the state's prison overcrowding.
   Bill Hoch, a Kansas City political consultant who managed the
campaign of Stephan's Democratic opponent in 1986, said Stephan
remains ``virtually unscathed'' by the Stingley case.
   ``I've been absolutely fascinated with the man's rapport with
people,'' he said. ``It goes to the fact that when Bob Stephan says
he cares about people, they believe him.''
</TEXT>
