<FIRST>r a AM-CholesterolCheck     04-23 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cholesterol Check,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cholesterol Checks Available during `CountDown' USA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Free cholesterol and blood pressure checks will
be available at hundreds of hospitals across the nation Wednesday
as part of ``CountDown USA.''
   April 26 is the second annual CountDown USA: The National Blood
Pressure and Cholesterol Check sponsored by Voluntary Hospitals of
America, a national association of nonprofit hospitals. More than
400,000 people took the tests last year.
   Cholesterol levels and blood pressures will be checked at 470
hospitals and other sites. The tests will be free at most sites, $5
at others.
   In addition, VHA will offer copies of low-cholesterol, low-fat,
low-salt recipes created by chefs associated with the James Beard
Foundation to promote heart-healthy diets.
   Testing site locations and other information is available by
calling 1-800-468-6842 between 8 a.m. and midnight EDT.
   Last week the hospital group released the results of a survey
which found that the number of Americans who know their cholesterol
level has nearly doubled in a year, and more than four in 10 say
they have changed their eating habits to cut their cholesterol.
   Among 1,016 people age 18 or over polled by the Gallup
Organization in January, 31 percent said they knew their
cholesterol level. A year before, when Gallup asked the same
question, just 17 percent knew.
   That increase in awareness ``clearly indicates that people are
getting the message'' that cholesterol can contribute to heart
disease, said Dr. DeWitt S. Goodman, head of an advisory board on
cholesterol for VHA, which commissioned the survey.
   The survey, conducted Jan. 9-22, found that about two-thirds of
respondents said they had undergone a blood test to check their
cholesterol level, and four in 10 said they had changed their diet
or eating habits in the past two years to reduce their cholesterol.
   The poll had a margin of sampling error of plus or minus 3
points.
</TEXT>
