<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-Activists     04-23 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia-Activists,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Activists Detained Prior To Planned Meeting With Hungarians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three prominent Czechoslovak activists
were detained Sunday on their way to meet Hungarian activists in
the Czechoslovak city of Bratislava, emigre sources said.
   Petr Uhl, Jan Urban and Petr Pospichal, all leading members of
the Charter 77 human rights group, were planning to meet
independent Hungarian activists at Bratislava's Carlton Hotel, the
London-based emigre publisher Palach Press reported.
   Anna Sabatova, Uhl's wife, said the three were picked up by
police as they got off the train from Prague.
   She said they were to meet three Hungarian activists. Two were
members of the Hungarian independent youth group, and third was the
Hungarian representative of an independent East European
information agency formed in December by activists from Poland,
Czechoslovakia, Hungary and the Soviet Union.
   Uhl, Pospichal and Urban are the Czechoslovak representatives of
the same group.
   On Friday, four Czechoslovak activists, including former Foreign
Minister Jiri Hajek, were prevented by police from traveling to
Warsaw where they had planned to take part in an international
human rights symposium.
</TEXT>
