<FIRST>r w AM-Environment-Polls Bjt   04-23 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Environment-Polls, Bjt,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Surveys Said To Track Growing Concern Over Environment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The professionals who monitor public opinion
say environmental issues have gained surprising political clout in
the last 20 years, leaving them unsurprised that President Bush
declares himself an environmentalist.
   A new study of public opinion polls, assembled by three leading
environmental organizations, traces a dramatic shift in American
attitudes toward the environment since the early 1970s and
pollsters suggest today's politicians are wise to listen.
   ``The issue of the environment has by now become an explosive
and decisive cutting edge in mainstream politics,'' writes pollster
Louis Harris in a contributing essay to the study.
   One need go no further than the March 24 oil spill in Alaska and
the public's perception of inept and confusing attempts by
government and industry to deal with it to show the interest that
Americans have in the environment, suggest the study's authors.
   In the aftermath of the spill, Bush's positive rating on
environmental issues, as reflected by a pair of Louis Harris &amp;
Associates polls, tumbled 21 points from 60 percent to 39 percent.
   Republican pollster W. Lance Tarrance Jr., suggests the Alaska
spill ``may shape the 1990 election debate (by) mobilizing voters
to feel more intensely about the need to act quickly and
decisively'' to protect the planet's resources.
   ``Protection of the environment ... has become a valence issue,
a basic American value,'' maintains Celinda C. Lake, a consultant
to Democratic candidates.
   She predicted that Bush's response in dealing with environmental
problems _ whether his actions are perceived as substantive or just
cosmetic _ ``will have an increasing strategic importance for
Democrats in national elections and in new congressional
districts.''
   The views of Harris, Tarrance and Ms. Lake were included as part
of an analysis of polling trends assembled by Americans for the
Environment, the Sierra Club and the National Wildlife Federation.
   Since 1970, the year of the first Earth Day and the dawn of the
modern environmental movement, public attitudes about environmental
protection have changed dramatically as shown by the result of
opinion polls cited in the analysis.
   Here are a few examples.
   _Concern about water and air pollution: In 1970, according to a
Gallup Poll, only 48 percent of those interviewed expressed concern
about polluted water. Last year in answer to the same question, 84
percent said they had such worries. People who were seriously
concerned about air pollution increased from 46 percent in 1970 to
73 percent in 1988.
   _Support for tougher environmental laws and regulations: In a
1977 survey by the Roper Organization, only 27 percent of the
respondents believed environmental laws and regulations were
inadequate. By 1983 when Roper asked the same question, 48 percent
felt that way. And last year, 53 percent of those interviewed by
Cambridge Reports said tougher environmental laws were needed.
   _Spending money on the environment: Last year 65 percent of the
respondents to a National Opinion Research Center poll said more
money should be spent on the environment, compared to 48 percent
who held that view in 1977. A series of Roper polls over roughly
the same time period reflected a somewhat smaller but also
significant increase.
   _Protecting wilderness: In answer to a Cambridge Reports poll in
1978, only 19 percent of the respondents chose preserving public
wilderness areas over opening them for energy development, a choice
of 65 percent. In answer to the same question last year 47 percent
favored preservation, compared to 42 percent for development.
   _Greenhouse effect problem: Surveys by Cambridge Reports show a
growing number of people consider global warming as a ``very
serious'' problem. In 1982, only 12 percent believed so, 24 percent
in 1986 and 39 percent last year.
   A variety of other polls cited by the study also reflect an
``unmistakable shift to a more pro-enviromental stance,'' says
David Baker, chairman of Americans for the Environment, a research
organization for a variety of environmental and conservation groups.
   ``The message,'' maintains Baker, ``is that people are mad as
hell about the way we treat our environment and they don't want to
take it anymore.''
</TEXT>
