<FIRST>r i AM-Romania-Debt     04-23 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Romania-Debt,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Romania Pays Off Its Debts But Problems Linger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By imposing harsh austerity measures,
Romania says it accomplished a feat this month that has eluded
scores of other nations: It paid off a huge foreign debt.
   The price, however, was steep and there is no indication it will
mean a better life for Romania's 23 million citizens, who have made
do with rationed food, gasoline, electricity and other essentials
for nearly a decade.
   President Nicolai Ceausescu, who has ruled Romania since 1965,
borrowed heavily from the West to industrialize, and by 1981 the
foreign debt had grown to $11 billion.
   He drove equally hard to repay the debt and reduced it to $6.6
billion in the mid-1980s. In a surprise announcement at a party
meeting last week, he said Romania had paid in full.
   ``This proves the might of the Romanian socialist economy and
opens wonderful prospects for ... Romania's advanc to communism,''
Ceausescu said.
   Although Romania accumulated the debt by industrializing, paying
back the money kept the country from buying foreign equipment
needed to make the industry run effectively. Foreign analysts now
say that buying such equipment may take priority over easing
austerity measures.
   Romania's debt stemmed partly from Ceausescu's choice of
energy-intensive industries such as petrochemicals and steel.
   The country's domestic oil reserves began to dwindle, however,
and Romania had to rely increasingly on imports to feed huge oil
refining complexes built in the 1960s and early 1970s when oil was
cheap. After 1981, Ceausescu ordered strict measures to save raw
materials and energy.
   Food rationing and prison terms of up to five years for hoarding
have been enforced since 1982. At the same time, food exports _
including farm products such as meat, ham and wheat _ increased.
   Since 1984, the government has periodically cut off heat and
light and banned driving cars for four months at a time to save
gasoline, which Romania has sold in recent years to the United
States and other countries to raise convertible currency.
   Gasoline is in such short supply that even the monthly ration of
five to eight gallons per car could not be supplied recently.
   Analysts predict that Romania will continue to export food and
other products to the West to earn hard currency for its industry,
and to the Soviet bloc in return for raw materials.
   Such a policy would do little in the short term to raise
Romania's standard of living, one of the lowest in Europe.
   These days Romanians must line up for hours to buy eggs, cheese
and butter. Crowds gather for ``tacimuri,'' small bags of chicken
wings and necks.
   The food shortages have created a ``language of misery,'' and
Romanians have coined idioms to describe the substandard food
available.
   ``Patriots,'' for example, are pig's feet, which being virtually
unexportable, ``never abandon their homeland.''
   Travelers from Romania have reported recent shortages of goods
such as cosmetics, soap, shampoo, building materials, shoes and
lingerie.
   Ceausescu, the object of a personality cult unrivaled in the
Soviet bloc, has not explained publicly why he wanted to repay the
debt so fast.
   The government constantly tells Romanians that the Ceausescu era
is an ``epoch of glory and grandeur'' and ``Romania's golden age.''
   Despite the consumer shortages, jokes abound.
   ``How can Romanians pay off their debt more easily? By
auctioning off the golden age,'' goes a recent one.
</TEXT>
