<FIRST>r a AM-PlaneDoorHearing     04-23 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane Door Hearing,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Safety Board To Probe 747 That Ripped Open Near Honolulu</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When federal investigators open a hearing Tuesday
into the reasons a forward cargo door was torn off a United
Airlines 747 jetliner, some of the best evidence will remain under
nearly 17,000 feet of water near Hawaii.
   But there may be efforts to raise the nine-foot-square door from
its watery grave 85 miles southwest of Honolulu.
   Nine people disappeared Feb. 24 when the door and part of the
aircraft fuselage, along with seats and luggage, were swept away as
Flight 811 climbed toward 23,000 feet at 300 mph.
   Though two engines conked out, pilot David Cronin managed to fly
the Sydney-bound plane back to Honolulu with no further loss of
life.
   Coast Guard cutters managed to recover some debris, including
part of the fuselage, but a big piece of metal _ believed to be the
800-pound door _ was seen on radar as it sank.
   Lee Dickinson, a member of the National Transportation Safety
Board, said he may be able to announce before the hearing starts
Tuesday morning whether there will be an effort to retrieve the
door. The hearing is expected to last three days.
   Even without the door, he said, investigators hope to learn much
more about the design and certification of the door on the 747-100,
which was one of the first jumbo jets built by the Seattle-based
Boeing Co.
   Those among the 13 testifying will also discuss maintenance,
inspection procedures and practices, human factors and details of a
1987 incident in which the cargo door on a Pan Am 747 opened
slightly on a flight out of London, he said.
   ``Next week, we will try to get a better understanding of the
`what' ... how everything pieced together'' as the sequence of
events occurred in a flash over the ocean.
   However, he said, pinpointing why the accident occurred would
take several more months of investigation.
   ``Boeing would be interested in having that cargo door back,''
said Jack Gamble, Boeing spokesman. ``A lot of questions could be
answered by looking at it.''
   Recovery of airplane parts from under thousands of feet of water
is not unprecedented. Huge sections of an Air India 747 blown by a
bomb into the sea near Ireland in 1985 were recovered, and the
flight recorder of a South African Airways plane was recovered from
the Indian Ocean in 1987.
   ``There is precedence for the deepwater type of retrieval
work,'' said Gamble. ``But it is expensive and it does take time.''
   Besides, said Rob Doughty spokesman for United, ``There may be
enough data without the door. But that's the NTSB's call.''
   Much of the investigation's focus has been on the cargo door,
which may have broken free in an explosive decompression when the
latching mechanism failed.
   United records indicated there had been problems with the door
before the accident, including a faulty seal and electrical
problems requiring the door to be closed manually rather than
electrically on several occasions. However, Doughty said it was
apparently not major repair work, and it was proper to close the
door manually as well as electrically.
   The FAA on March 3 issued an emergency order requiring all U.S.
airlines to reinforce within 30 days the relatively lightweight
aluminum latch mechanisms with steel, so the doors would be less
vulnerable to damage caused by improper closing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
