<FIRST>r a AM-JunkMailMuddle     04-23 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Junk Mail Muddle,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rural Mailman Is Suspended For Using Term `Junk Mail'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEG REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rural postal carrier who called
bulk-rate advertising ``junk mail'' in a newspaper interview, and
said the best parts of his job were payday and quitting time, will
be suspended for two weeks without pay.
   Richard Mendenhall, a 23-year veteran of the U.S. Postal
Service, will be suspended from May 20 to June 2 for ``conduct
unbecoming a postal employee,'' according to his suspension
documents. The suspension will cost him about $1,300 in pay, he
said.
   Mendenhall, 47, says some of his co-workers at the Xenia Post
Office use ``junk mail'' to describe many of the third-class
mailings he delivers each day.
   ``The public calls it junk mail, but the post office wants it
called BBM, bulk-rate business mail,'' Mendenhall said by telephone
Saturday night from Xenia, a town of about 24,000 in west-central
Ohio.
   ``I wasn't bad-mouthing the post office or anything. I just was
saying what other people say.''
   An entry in the third college edition of Webster's New World
Dictionary defines junk mail as advertisements or solicitations
``mailed in large quantities, often by third-class and addressed
only to `occupant.'''
   Xenia Postmaster Joyce Clay-Sanders refused to discuss the
suspension. Kent Hartway, an official in the labor relations
division of the Dayton Post Office, which has authority over the
Xenia office, also refused to comment.
   A March 27 story in The Xenia Daily Gazette quoted Mendenhall as
saying he had not adopted the post office's preferred term for his
daily load of bulk-rate advertising.
   ``I still call it junk,'' he said in the story. ``It was junk 20
years ago. The customers will tell me that, too.''
   Mendenhall also complained about glossy folders in which
multiple circulars are placed as part of an advertising device
known as ``marriage mail.''
   ``They slide all over the place on you,'' he said. ``It comes
apart and becomes garbage.''
   Mendenhall estimates that he carries 800 to 900 pieces of junk
mail, including catalogs, on his 47-mile daily route.
   He also roused the ire of his supervisors by saying his favorite
parts of the job were payday and quitting time.
   ``Everybody feels that way,'' he said. ``They're fussing even
about that.''
   Mendenhall does not belong to a union, but said he would file a
grievance with his supervisor this week.
</TEXT>
