<FIRST>r w AM-BettyWright     04-23 0739</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Betty Wright,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mrs. Wright's Friends Rally to Her Side</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Wright-Probe Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Betty Wright's friends have rallied to her
side as she fights allegations that she and her husband, House
Speaker Jim Wright, violated House rules by accepting impermissible
gifts.
   ``She is a strong individual and she's always been very nice to
me,'' said Phyllis Coehlo, the wife of Rep. Tony Coehlo, D-Calif.,
the House majority whip.
   Mrs. Wright, an adoptive Texan who came to Washington as a
secretary in Wright's congressional office 24 years ago, has tried
to avoid the limelight since the House Ethics Committee concluded
last week that her husband violated 69 rules. Some of the
allegations stem from her employment by Wright's friends.
   In an interview with the Washington Post, Mrs. Wright staunchly
defended the couples' conduct, calling her husband ``the most
honest man I know.''
   ``Neither Jim nor I ever intended to evade the law in any way,
shape or form,'' she said. ``My God, he's been there for 30 years.
Why all of a sudden would he do a shady thing like that?''
   One of the allegations made by the ethics committee was that
Mrs. Wright failed to do any work for a company called Mallightco,
jointly owned by Wright and George Mallick, a developer in Fort
Worth, Texas, the city Wright represents. Mallightco paid Mrs.
Wright $18,000 a year between 1981 and 1984.
   Mrs. Wright, 65, bristled at the suggestion of the ethics
committee that she wasn't qualified to handle investments for
Mallightco.
   ``Common sense and judgment stand for something,'' she said. ``I
know lots of men who don't have specific business experience and
have made lots of money in business.''
   Mrs. Wright's friends described her as an organized, take-charge
person whose administrative skills were honed in the years she
spent working as a secretary on Capitol Hill and in Texas.
   ``She's more of a doer than I am,'' said Mrs. Coehlo, a
long-time personal secretary to Rep. Andrew Jacobs Jr., D-Ind.
   ``She's a very organized person,'' said Dick Sullivan, Mrs.
Wright's former boss on the House Public Works Committee.
   The life of Betty Wright, the former Betty Hay, has been the
kind that many women dream about, moving from Capitol Hill
secretary to the wife of one of the country's most powerful figures.
   Raised in St. Louis, Mrs. Wright was the only child of a broken
home: she never knew her father and her stepfather divorced her
mother when Betty Hay was a child.
   When her mother contracted rheumatic fever, Betty Hay, then a
teen-ager, turned her love of tap-dancing into profit, dancing in
nightclub chorus lines.
   Later, she graduated from secretarial school and moved to Texas
with her then-husband, a pilot. They soon divorced.
   In 1965, Betty Hay took a job with Wright's congressional office
and moved to Washington. Later, she shifted to the House public
works committee.
   When Wright separated from his wife in 1970, he began dating
Betty Hay. They married in 1972, the year his divorce was final.
The couple, who have a large house in suburb McLean, Va., have no
children together. Wright has four from his previous marriage.
   In 1976, Wright became majority leader and his wife left her
$24,000-a-year job on the public works committee.
   In 1984, she began a three-year job for the Pacific Institute, a
Seattle-based institute that teaches techniques of self-motivation
and counts Democratic members of Congress among its clients.
   Mrs. Wright told the Post she received $36,000 annually for her
part-time work as a customer representative for the institute,
which is run by Lou and Diane Tice. The Wrights, who attended a
three-day institute seminar several years ago, are good friends of
the Tices.
   The former communications director of the Pacific Institute, Bob
Hardwick, said he warned his bosses in 1987 that having Mrs. Wright
on the payroll was ``improper.''
   ``They insisted there wasn't anything illegal about it,'' said
Hardwick. ``I said, `I don't care. It's improper. It bends ethics.
I don't care what your intent is. You're going to damage your
friends,''' said Hardwick.
   Additionally, Mrs. Wright serves on the board of the National
Theater in Washington.
   Despite her outside interests, Mrs. Wright's friends said her
No. 1 priority has been attending to the health and wardrobe of her
husband.
   ``She really looks after Jim _ hoping he gets enough sleep and
things like that,'' Mrs. Coehlo said.
</TEXT>
