<FIRST>r i AM-Algeria     04-23 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Algeria,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soaring Prices Spur Protests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RACHID KHIARI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumers called for a boycott of some
food products to protest soaring prices, and many merchants
retaliated by closing their shops in the latest tensions over
Algeria's crumbling economy.
   Protests against rising prices have spread in recent weeks,
triggering occasional violence. Several dozen people were injured
April 16 and many shops were looted in a riot at the market in the
southwestern village of Aflou.
   Authorities said two policemen were among the injured and that
about 50 people were arrested.
   The Commerce Ministry has promised to enforce price controls
more strictly, and the state-run press has blamed the increases on
``speculators'' and ``those who starve the people.''
   In Algiers and Oran, the biggest cities in this North African
Arab country, posters have gone up calling on consumers to boycott
meat and other products whose prices shot up almost overnight.
   In reply, many merchants went on strike Saturday and threatened
to keep their stores closed if the boycott calls continued.
   ``I don't have to boycott meat. I can't afford to buy it at
these prices,'' Salah Laribi, a 47-year-old father of six, said in
an unusually deserted Algiers market Sunday.
   Beef has jumped in price to about $11.35 a pound, almost double
the going rate a few weeks ago. Tomatoes have doubled in price, to
$1.50 per pound, and onions have quadrupled in cost.
   The Algerian dinar officially is worth 16.7 cents, but black
market traders offer at least five times the official rate for
dollars and other hard currencies.
   It is not entirely clear why prices have shot up so suddenly,
although the Algerian economy has been crippled in recent years by
tumbling oil prices. Oil and gas account for more than 95 percent
of the country's export earnings.
   Frequent strikes by government employees and workers for
public-sector companies have caused still more problems in the past
six months, especially a strike that has paralyzed major ports at
Skikda and Arsez.
   Violent demonstrations that claimed hundreds of lives in October
began as protests of high prices but turned into an attack on state
control of the economy and the authoritarian socialist government.
   The violence prompted President Chadli Bendjedid to institute a
series of constitutional reforms that are to pave the way for a
multiparty system.
   In recent months, about 30 new political parties have been
formed, but they have been discreet in their activities while
awaiting government action to legalize them.
</TEXT>
