<FIRST>r a AM-WomanAssaulted     04-23 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Woman Assaulted,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Arraigned in Beating, Rape of Jogger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight youths arraigned Sunday on charges of
beating and raping a Central Park jogger joked about the attack and
one called it ``fun,'' officials said.
   The teen-agers, age 14 to 17, joked, sang a rap song and showed
no remorse during their first night in jail, according to published
reports.
   ``It was fun,'' one of the suspects, 15-year-old Yusef Salaam,
said in a written confession, according to Gerald McKelvey, a
spokesman for the Manhattan district attorney's office.
   The victim, a 28-year-old Wall Street investment banker whose
skull was fractured by a pipe and a brick in the Wednesday night
attack, remained in a coma Sunday, said Richard Conte, an
administrator at Metropolitan Hospital.
   The attack on the woman came while the pack of youths was
``wilding'' in the park _ their term for a rampage of random
violence and thievery, police said. The pack started with about 30
members who beat or terrorized nine people before splitting up when
a police van cruised by.
   Seven of the youths made videotaped statements to police; Salaam
gave a written statement, McKelvey said.
   Assistant District Attorney Elizabeth Lederer told Manhattan
Criminal Court Judge Charles Solomon about the statements at the
arraignment. Solomon ordered all eight held without bail on charges
of second-degree attempted murder, first-degree rape and
first-degree assault.
   ``Most of the statements tend to say that others did things
while `I was there and just watched,' or held her down,'' McKelvey
said.
   Friends and relatives of the suspects expressed shock and some
were doubtful of the youths' involvement.
   Police think about 12 youths were in the underbrush by a roadway
when the victim jogged by alone about 10 p.m.
   According to accounts from investigators published in New York
Newsday, the Daily News and the New York Post, the group knocked
her down with the metal pipe and gagged her with her clothing.
While some held her down and fondled her, at least four raped her.
   At one point, the victim was able to scratch the face of one
attacker, identified as Kevin Richardson, 14. She was again struck
by the pipe, rocks or bricks, and also cut by a knife. They left
her for dead, investigators said, and passersby found her 3{ hours
later.
   In a nearby police stationhouse, the suspects whistled at
policewomen, laughed about the attack and compared notes on what
they had told police, the newspapers quoted investigators as saying.
   They ``appeared empty of emotion ... as if they were talking
about something insignificant,'' the Daily News quoted an
unidentified police source as saying.
   At one point, the suspects began singing the rap song ``Wild
Thing,'' the News reported.
   ``They were bragging to each other about what they had told us
and comparing notes,'' one police source told the Post. ``They were
discussing what they had done and they were laughing about it.''
   The Post said it interviewed one of the eight suspects, who said
the woman put up a fight and was punched unconscious, then raped by
three people. ``We was just going on a spree, going out and
harassing, you know,'' the boy told the Post.
   Besides Salaam and Richardson, the other suspects were
identified as Antron McCray, 15; Clarence Thomas, 14; Raymond
Santana, 14; Steve Lopez, 15; Kharey Wise, 16; and Michael Brisco,
17. All of the suspects are being tried as adults, but only Wise
and Brisco could be sentenced as adults.
