<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     04-23 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polish Opposition Approves Independent Candidates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition activists led by Solidarity
chairman Lech Walesa on Sunday approved 252 independent candidates
for legislative elections in June. Walesa insisted he will not run.
   The national Solidarity Citizens Committee approved 252
candidates eligible to run for all 100 seats in a new Senate and
161 seats in the existing 460-member upper house known as the Sejm.
   Candidates for the nine remaining seats open to the opposition
will be selected in the next few days, Solidarity national
spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz told a news conference after the
four-hour meeting.
   Government-opposition talks ended in an agreement April 5 to
lift a seven-year ban on Solidarity and cleared the way for the
most democratic elections in Poland's postwar history. The labor
union officially became legal April 17.
   The government agreed to lift the ban in exchange for political
and economic cooperation from the opposition.
   In his opening speech Sunday to delegates gathered at Warsaw
University, Walesa appealed for unity as the now-legal union enters
``the new situation'' of building democracy in communist Poland.
   Walesa reiterated that he did not intend to run for the new,
freely elected Senate or the Sejm seats open to the opposition. The
Solidarity chief, a 1983 Nobel Peace laureate, said he wanted to be
free to lead the opposition and his union, the first independent
labor movement in the East bloc.
   However, many of the country's leading union and political
activists plan to run as candidates, including longtime Walesa
associates Bogdan Lis and Leszek Kaczynski; senior Solidarity
adviser Jacek Kuron; historian and Walesa adviser Bronislaw
Geremek; political essayist Adam Michnik, and prominent film
director Andrzej Wajda.
   The elections are scheduled June 4 with a runoff June 18.
   Onyszkiewicz said a draft of the opposition's platform was being
re-edited following Sunday's discussions and would be ready Monday.
   Solidarity leaders said the opposition faces tremendous time
pressure in preparing for elections. They also acknowledged a lack
of experience in how to run campaigns.
   ``Social knowledge about the procedure of these elections is
close to zero. We have to start our work on that very soon,'' said
Kuron at the news conference.
   Walesa, who had just returned from a four-day trip to Rome where
he made appeals for Western aid to rebuild Poland's ailing economy,
appealed for opposition unity in his speech to the meeting Sunday.
   Walesa said the opposition was, in a sense, undergoing its most
difficult time. ``One thing is ending, and the new one has not
started functioning yet,'' he said.
   ``It is a new situation in which we have to combine people of
struggle with those of work. And that's why I strongly appeal to
you, let's forget about group or individual interests,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
