<DOCNO> AP890423-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-89 1529EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-HousingEvictions Bjt   04-23 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housing Evictions, Bjt,0723</SECOND>
<HEAD>Public Housing Tenants Balance Safety vs. Civil Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT SONNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public housing tenants caught in a crossfire
of gangs and dope peddlers see a tough new eviction policy as a
step toward a safer neighborhood despite opposition from defenders
of civil rights.
   Omaha Housing Authority Director Robert Armstrong calls his
agency's eviction policy the toughest in the nation, and U.S.
Housing and Urban Development Secretary Jack Kemp has praised it as
an example others should follow to help rid housing projects of
drugs and gangs.
   The Omaha agency adopted the policy last week, arming itself
with the power to evict tenants who themselves or whose children or
other household members _ including guests _ are suspected of
certain crimes.
   Kemp last week announced HUD actions aimed at easing the
eviction process for local agencies that operate federally
subsidized housing projects. Among other things, HUD is making drug
offenses a specific violation of leases.
   Last month, Alexandria, Va., Mayor James P. Moran secured a
waiver from HUD rules that allow a tenant to appeal eviction to an
administrative panel or court. The mayor asked for the waiver to
speed evictions of suspected drug dealers. HUD agreed after being
satisfied that tenants' rights, including the right to take their
complaints to court, were adequately protected under state law.
   In Omaha, tenants' leases have been amended to explain they may
be evicted if drug or violent criminal activity is suspected inside
or outside the project ``without regard to whether or not any
person whose conduct is at issue has been arrested, charged or
convicted.''
   Armstrong said he will review each case, and evictions will not
be automatic. He said residents will be allowed to appeal in court
and can avoid eviction by arranging for counseling or other
rehabilitation.
   However, critics say the leases violate tenants' rights because
evictions are allowed based on activity off the grounds and without
regard for whether anyone has been charged.
   ``They are basically evicting people because they have criminal
characters,'' said Gary Fischer, senior attorney for housing for
the Omaha Legal Aid Society.
   Armstrong and other community leaders said most public housing
residents back the tough policy.
   ``I haven't heard anyone who lives there say they are against
it,'' said Jesse Sharpe, director of community services for Family
Service, a United Way agency.
   Residents of Omaha's Logan Fontenelle housing project, which is
so violent it has been nicknamed ``Vietnam,'' say the sound of
gunfire often punctuates the night and drugs are dealt openly.
Police have stepped up foot patrols.
   ``I can't let my kids play outside,'' said Tina Jones, who lives
near ``Crack Corner'' in the project. ``My little boy, he's been in
the middle of two shootings. My daughter picked up a needle on the
way to school.''
   Francis Smith, an OHA board member who has lived in public
housing for 22 years, said she supports the policy as a last resort.
   ``I didn't like the idea at first because of the idea of
evicting the whole family because one member of the family got
caught with drugs away from home,'' Ms. Smith said.
   Kemp said last week that authorities will have to consider the
role parents played in drug activity by their children before
evicting entire families.
   Most youths in the projects live with a single mother or with
grandparents who may not always know what the child is doing, said
Avoca Mason, chairman of the Black Ministers Commission.
   Fischer said the OHA should have no authority to regulate
activity off the project grounds. ``The housing authority is saying
by this policy that we are requiring the parent to be omniscient,''
the lawyer said.
   OHA attorney Steven Riekes said the policy was prompted by the
1988 Federal Anti-Drug Abuse Act, which allows evictions based on
criminal activity but does not define such activity.
   ``If the tenant was selling cocaine from his unit and for some
reason he is not arrested for it, nevertheless the Housing
Authority has proof and a preponderance of evidence _ if it can
prove in a civil eviction suit that the person is using cocaine _
then that is all that is necessary,'' Riekes said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
