<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Election     04-23 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Election,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moscow Mayor Rejects Second Election Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moscow's mayor has pulled out of a second race for
a congressional seat he failed to win a month ago, saying he will
concentrate instead on solving problems in Moscow.
   ``Voters justly demand quick solution of serious social problems
that have been piling up for decades,'' Mayor Valery Saikin said in
a letter printed on the front page of the newspaper Moskovskaya
Pravda on Sunday.
   He cited housing problems, consumer goods shortages, public
transportation, public health, and the environment.
   Saikin was among several dozen Communist Party and government
leaders rejected by voters March 26 in the first nationally
contested elections in 70 years. Party and government leaders in
Leningrad, Kiev and other large cities also were rejected, even
though many ran unopposed.
   Saikin ran against Nina Ageeva for a seat in the new,
2,250-member Congress of Peoples Deputies. Ms. Ageeva received 24.8
percent of the vote, and Saikin received 42.5 percent.
   The winner needed a majority to avoid a new election.
   Saikin said in the letter that he was turning down nominations
by two work collectives to run again in elections May 14.
</TEXT>
