<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon     04-23 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christians Stranded After Ship Turns Back</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Christians trying to flee
their besieged enclave north of Beirut were left stranded Sunday
after a Cypriot ship heading to Lebanon to rescue them turned back
under Syrian artillery fire.
   The 4,000-ton Baroness M had been scheduled to anchor off the
port of Jounieh, the Christians' only sea link with the outside
world, after darkness fell to pick up some of more than 3,000
Christians waiting there.
   But port sources in Jounieh, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the ferry turned back before it reached the port and was
sailing for Larnaca, on the south coast of Cyprus, 130 miles
northeast of Lebanon.
   Port officials in Cyprus said the Baroness M was carrying only
its crew and a handful of passengers who had sought to get into the
Christian enclave.
   Despite the barrage around Jounieh, port officials in Cyprus
reported earlier that another ferry, the Larnaca Rose, arrived in
Larnaca Sunday with 650 Christians after it ran a gauntlet of
Syrian fire Saturday night.
   Syrian troops and their Moslem Druse allies fired more than 100
shells and rockets into the Christian enclave north of Beirut
Sunday, seeking to sever the Christians' escape route.
   Police said about 100 shells and rockets exploded around
Jounieh, where more than 3,000 people are waiting to be picked up,
and a coastal strip running north to the ancient port of Byblos.
   They said the shellfire caused no casualties and did little
damage.
   The firing was minor compared to the fierce barrages that
hammered the 310-square-mile enclave for the last six weeks in some
of the most ferocious barrages of the 14-year-old civil war.
   By police count, at least 270 people have been killed and nearly
1,000 wounded since the battles erupted March 8.
   The artillery and rocket duels between mainly Christian army
units led by army commander Gen. Michel Aoun and an alliance of
Syrians and their militia allies died down Wednesday.
   Aoun, 53, also heads the country's Christian government, which
is vying for legitimacy with a rival Moslem government. He has
declared a ``war of liberation'' against the Syrians, who have
40,000 soldiers in Lebanon under an Arab League mandate to keep the
peace in Lebanon's 14-year civil war.
   Despite the lull, the Syrians have continued to target Jounieh,
12 miles north of Beirut. They aim to prevent supplies getting to
Aoun's forces and halt the ferry service to Cyprus.
   The two ferries have evacuated more than 13,000 Christians and
foreigners since March 8.
   They no longer risk docking in Jounieh. Instead, they anchor
offshore and passengers are shuttled out in small boats under cover
of darkness.
   Beirut residents, traumatized by the weeks of almost non-stop
bombardment, have been living without electricity or water and
suffering from acute food, bread and fuel shortages.
   The French Navy tanker Penhors, loaded with 6,000 tons of fuel
oil sent by Paris to aid the Lebanese, docked Sunday at the Zahrani
oil terminal in south Lebanon to unload one-third of its cargo for
a Druse-controlled power plant in nearby Jiye.
   Police said the Penhors will sail to the Christian harbor of
Zouk later Sunday to unload the rest of its cargo at the main power
plant for Beirut.
   A chartered transport plane carrying 80 tons of medical and food
supplies from Italy landed at Larnaca Sunday. The supplies will be
shipped to Lebanon later.
   A second plane, also carrying 80 tons of Italian relief aid, was
scheduled to arrive in Larnaca Monday.
   French Foreign Minister Roland Dumas said in Paris Sunday that
at France's request, the permament members of the U.N. Security
Council _ the United States, the Soviet Union, China, France and
Britain _ have agreed to give Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar a mandate to work with the Arab League to seek peace in
Lebanon.
</TEXT>
