<FIRST>r a AM-AgingMarin     04-23 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aging Marin,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marin County Residents To Be State's Oldest, Focus of Research</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN RAFAEL, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marin County's image may be that of
steaming hot tubs and youthful hedonists gamboling in paradise, but
over the next decade residents may be thinking more about Medicare
than child care.
   After the year 2000, the county will have the oldest population
in the state. The graying of Marin will be the focus of research
about the aging process and a Ponce de Leon-like attempt to
``arrest the downside of getting old.''
   According to a just-released report by the county's Agency on
Aging, Marin's population 60 and older will increase about 48
percent by the turn of the century. The county will have the oldest
population in California while tiny Mono County in the Sierra
Nevada will have the youngest.
   In 1970, 11 percent of Marin residents were 60 and older; that
number climbed to 14 percent in 1980, 16.5 percent in 1985 and
continues to increase. Almost 70 percent of Marinites over 60 own
their own homes and have no plans to sell or move elsewhere,
according to local aging experts.
   ``Persons 85-plus are now the fastest-growing age group in the
county,'' said the report. ``Between 1985 and 2020, this age group
will almost triple.''
   The report predicted that almost one out of three Marin
residents will be 60 or older by the year 2020. The median age is
expected to rise from 33.6 in 1980 to 42.6 in 2000 and 47.7 in 2020
_ almost 10 years older than the projected statewide median of 38.1.
   And one out of every four elderly people interviewed for the
report complained of financial problems, with 45 percent living on
annual incomes of less than $10,000.
   To try to head off trouble in this paradise, and elsewhere, the
Buck Center for Research in Aging has hired Dr. Jacob Brody, a
leading expert on the cause and control of disease, to help study
Marin's aging population.
   ``This is a good group to study because we know they're not
going to retire to Florida,'' joked Brody. ``They're still going to
be there to study when they're even older.''
   The county's eldery provide a ``very stable, intelligent,
well-educated'' group on whom ``basic research can be done to make
it better to be old for all of us,'' Brody said.
   Brody, dean of public health at the University of Illinois, and
William Satariano, an epidemiologist and associate professor of
public health at the University of California, will try to
distinguish between the aging process and the disease process.
   ``We want to divert thinking away from cancer, heart attacks and
strokes'' and toward common ailments whose alleviation will make
elderly life more fun and less burdensome, Brody said.
   ``We want to know how basic science can postpone these
conditions that we just assume are part of getting old,'' Brody
said. ``We want to arrest the downside of being old.''
   The Buck study will look at 2,000 volunteers, with 500 people in
each the age groups 55-64, 65-74, 75-84, and 85 and older.
</TEXT>
