<SECOND>AM-Sudan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0664,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Injured in Arson Attacks on Mosque and Church</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with government meeting, Cabinet
calling for self-restraint. Pick up 3rd pvs, `The newspaper...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslems set fire to a Roman Catholic
Church's relief center and Christians retaliated by burning a
nearby mosque, newspapers said Sunday. Four people were reported
hurt, including a nun and a Moslem cleric.
   Police sent reinforcements to prevent further clashes between
Moslems and Christians in Thawra, a slum area in Omdurman across
the Nile River from Khartoum.
   Also Sunday, the government of Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi met to
discuss the weekend violence.
   Information Minister Hussein Suleiman Abu-Salih said the
Cabinet, in an attempt to prevent the situation from deteriorating,
called for self-restraint and began contacts with various political
parties.
   The newspaper Sudani said the violence began Friday when an
unidentified Moslem clergyman criticized the presence of the
church-run relief center in remarks to worshipers attending noon
prayers. The newspaper said the clergyman led the arson attack on
the church.
   On Saturday, a group of Christians from the church set fire to
the mosque in retaliation, witnesses said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Sudani and the Sudan Times said the injured included Sister
Maria Victoria, a nun at the church; the Moslem clergyman and at
least two other people.
   Police had no estimate of the damages, and the extent of the
injuries was not known.
   The church and relief center were set up in Sudan in 1985 by the
Missionaries of Charity, the worldwide missionary movement of
Catholic nuns and Nobel laureate Mother Teresa. The center houses
about 140 poor and sick people.
   In 1986, the nuns filed a complaint to police, saying they were
being intimidated by members of the mosque. No action was taken.
   Omdurman Police Chief Ahmed Murtada Bakri told reporters the
motives for the weekend arson attacks were ``personal'' and
religious, but he said investigations showed no link between the
incidents and any political groups.
   The majority of Sudan's 22 million inhabitants are Moslem,
except for about 6 million Christians and animists who live mainly
in the south. Christians and animists comprise the rebel movement
that has been fighting the Moslem-dominated government since 1983
for greater autonomy.
   In a related development, authorities cited ``order and security
reasons'' in canceling a demonstration organized by southern
parties Sunday to support peace talks with the rebels.
</TEXT>
