<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Youth     04-23 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Youth,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungary Youth Group Drops Communist Affiliation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's Communist Youth Union has
voted to drop its explicit party affiliation and back the party's
reform wing, news reports said Sunday.
   During a weekend conference, the group voted by a two-thirds
majority to change its name to the Hungarian Democratic Youth
Federation, the official MTI news agency and state radio reported.
   The movement agreed it would not accept the direction of any
single party, MTI reported.
   The union steadily lost members in recent years as it came under
criticism for not representing young people's interests.
   An independent youth group, FIDESZ, was established last year.
It has gained considerable political influence, although it has
said it does not wish to become a political party.
   Imre Nagy, who became the Communist Youth Union's leader at a
national conference in November, was elected chairman of the new
federation by 70 percent of the vote, radio said. Nagy, a
32-year-old mathematician, is viewed as a committed reformer.
</TEXT>
