<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-89 1940EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines     04-23 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Propose Multiparty Alliance Against U.S. Bases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist-led National Democratic
Front urged major political parties Sunday to form an alliance with
rebel forces to press for the removal of U.S. military bases.
   The front, whose 12 underground organizations include the
Communist Party of the Philippines and the New People's Army, made
the proposal in a statement delivered to news organizations on its
16th anniversary.
   ``We are building the solid foundation of the sovereign people's
democratic mgovernment, which can be reasonably expected to emerge
within the next decade,'' said the statement issued by Satur
Ocampo, a negotiator in failed peace talks with President Corazon
Aquino's government.
   Ocampo said groups opposed to ``U.S. intervention'' in the
country are welcome to the front and could form part of a
consultative body that would determine the rebel government's basic
elements.
   ``Major traditional political parties and independent groups
could form an alliance with the national democratic forces for the
immediate dismantling of the U.S. military bases and total
opposition to U.S. intervention in the nation's affairs,'' Ocampo
said.
   The offer came a day after New People's Army rebels claimed
responsibility for the killing of U.S. Army Col. James Rowe, who
was ambushed Friday on his way to work in suburban Manila.
   The rebels said Rowe was slain because he was a ``direct
participant'' in the government's counterinsurgency program. The
51-year-old colonel served as chief of the ground forces of the
Joint U.S.-Military Advisory Group, which provides training and
logistical support for the Philippine armed forces.
   The United States maintains six military installations in the
Philippines, including Clark Air Base and Subic Bay Naval Base, two
of its largest facilities overseas. About 40,000 soldiers and
dependents occupy the bases, while another 100,000 Americans reside
in the country.
   Last week, the front offered to declare a unilateral cease-fire
and enter peace talks if Mrs. Aquino promised to close the bases by
1991, when their lease expires. The front added that it was
``determined to make U.S. imperialism pay dearly for the continuing
stay of its bases.''
   Mrs. Aquino, who refuses to say if she will support the bases'
extension, brushed aside the rebel proposal and said there must be
no conditions for renewing negotiations. The first attempt for a
peaceful settlement of the 20-year-old rebellion collapsed two
years ago over differences between the government and rebel agendas.
   Government troops tightened security around U.S. installations
and at Manila's international airport following Friday's attack,
which came two weeks after rebels bombed a U.S. communications
station in the northern province of Benguet. There were no injuries
in the bombing.
</TEXT>
