<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Soccer     04-23 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Soccer,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Memorial Services For Soccer Fans Killed In Stadium Crush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIVERPOOL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anfield Stadium closed its gates
Sunday evening, bringing to an end the weeklong procession of
soccer fans paying respects to the 95 people killed in Britain's
worst sports disaster.
   The tragedy occurred April 15 at the Hillsborough Stadium in
Sheffield, 60 miles east of Liverpool, during the opening minutes
of a game between Liverpool and Nottingham Forest teams.
   In Sheffield, Archbishop of York John Habgood told the
congregation at a memorial service not to lash out in anger until
more is known about what caused the deadly crush at a section of
the stadium packed by fans from Liverpool.
   During the past week an estimated 1 million people made their
way through Anfield Stadium, the home of the Liverpool team. About
half of the field was covered with flowers and scarves of soccer
teams from throughout the country.
   After a brief religious observance at the stadium Sunday the
last mourners left and police closed the gates.
   Sheffield's 1,000-seat Cathedral of St. Peter and St. Paul was
filled to overflowing for the memorial service that was carried by
louspeakers to people gathered oustide.
   They heard the Anglican archbishop advise against trying to find
a scapegoat for the deaths.
   He said disasters are brought about by ``mistakes, misjudgments
and mischances coming together in a deadly combination. There are
times when it is right to be angry, but anger which is allowed to
spill over before the true facts are known, anger based on
speculation, anger directed at those who cannot answer back, is
merely destructive.''
   Anger now, ``when so much is uncertain ... can only make the
task of learning from this disaster that much harder,'' the
archbishop said.
   Within hours after the disaster there were accusations against
police and also some fans. A government investigation is under way.
   A memorial service also was held in Nottingham.
</TEXT>
