<FIRST>r a AM-InaugurationBicentennial     04-23 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inauguration Bicentennial,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mock Washington's Arrival Kicks Off Bicentennial Celebration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amid the boutiques and trendy eateries of 20th
century lower Manhattan, George Washington stepped off a barge
Sunday to commence a week of events marking the 200th anniversary
of his inauguration.
   The Washington look-alike was really Philadelphia actor William
Sommerfield, who was greeted at South Street Seaport by cannon fire
and a crowd of more than 3,000 as a marching band played everything
from Irving Berlin to Michael Jackson.
   ``He looks just like him,'' said Kris Visconti, 14.
   Mayor Edward I. Koch was there, too. He welcomed ``George
Washington, reincarnated, back to New York City'' and presented him
with a framed proclamation.
   Sommerfield spoke briefly to the crowd through one of those
new-fangled microphones that did not exist the first time around.
``I cannot conceal the painful emotion I feel at being called upon
to serve as president of the United States,'' he told them.
   He had crossed the choppy harbor from Elizabeth, New Jersey, in
a small wooden barge, a replica of a 17th-century vessel, which was
covered with a red canopy and decorated with garlands of evergreen.
   In New Jersey earlier in the day, Sommerfield greeted 200 newly
naturalized citizens and encountered a bit of civil unrest from
modern residents of the colonial city of Elizabethtown.
   Nearly 1,500 people, a third of them protesting recent municipal
layoffs, lined a main Elizabeth intersection in windy 40-degree
weather to catch a glimpse of the mock Revolutionary War hero.
   The new citizens, many of them Asian and Hispanic, were sworn in
outside the Union County Courthouse, which was draped in red, white
and blue bunting and colonial American flags.
   ``Two hundred years ago to this date, the president-elect of our
nation arrived in Elizabethtown, New Jersey,'' said Superior Court
Judge Edward W. Beglin Jr. ``There is a bridge from those events to
today that will by symbolized in these proceedings by the
acceptation of 200 citizens into citizenship.''
   Across the street from the re-enactment, about 500 policemen,
firefighters and their families demonstrated their anger over
recent layoffs in the financially ailing city.
   Mayor Thomas Dunn, who was absent from Sunday's festivities, on
April 14 laid off 144 police officers, firefighters and emergency
medical technicians and 81 other municipal employees. Dunn said the
layoffs were necessary to close a $26 million deficit caused by a
lack of state aid.
   Sommerfield began his re-enactment of the inaugural voyage in
Mount Vernon, Va., last Sunday. The carriage the actor was riding
in broke down less than 100 feet into the 250-mile trek to New York
City, however, and he had to continue on by van.
   His barge Sunday was pulled by a Coast Guard boat most of the
way. But for photo opportunities in front of the Statue of Liberty
and Battery Park, it was propelled by 10 oarsmen.
   Four old-style schooners, a replica of the 18th-century British
gunboat, the H.M.S. Rose, and numerous police and pleasure crafts
accompanied the barge.
   When it arrived at the port, Washington strode down the dock and
acknowledged the cheers of the crowd before climbing a platform
filled with city officials.
   Two-hundred years ago, Washington actually landed at Murray's
Wharf, at Wall Street, not South Street Seaport a few blocks north.
Eschewing a fancy coach, the real Washington strolled up narrow
Wall Street, bowing and tipping his hat to cheering admirers.
</TEXT>
