<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     04-23 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Laments Killing But Warns Against Brute Force and Witch Hunts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCOS ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The archbishop of San Salvador
on Sunday denounced the ``cold blooded'' assassination of the
attorney general but pleaded against a reaction of brute force and
witch hunts.
   Monsignor Arturo Rivera Damas said he lamented Wednesday's
killing of Attorney General Roberto Garcia Alvardo.
   ``But with equal vehemence we want to guard against the
temptation to respond to this violence with indiscriminately
exercised brute force,'' the Roman Catholic archbishop said in his
Sunday homily. ``We hope that the raids on union locals and
humanitarian groups are not the prelude to a witch hunt.''
   Garcia Alvardo was killed in the explosion of a bomb placed on
his vehicle. He was a prominent member of the right-wing Republican
Nationalist Alliance, or Arena.
   A week earlier a bomb damaged the residence of Vice
President-elect Francisco Merino, also of Arena.
   Security forces responded to the bombings by raiding several
union headquarters and the offices of religious and humanitarian
groups accused by rightists of sympathizing with left-wing rebels.
At least 70 people were detained.
   Rivera Damas said the church is seeking the release of detainees
not charged with any crime.
   Violence has increased since the March 19 presidential election
won by Arena candidate Alfredo Cristiani over the incumbent
Christian Democrats.
   Right-wing death squads were blamed for thousands of killings of
suspected leftists during the early years of the 9-year-old civil
war between the rebels and U.S.-backed government.
   The Arena founder, retired army Maj. Roberto D'Aubuisson, has
been accused of links with the death squads. He denies the
allegations.
   Rivera Damas also defended a Spanish priest that Merino claimed
belonged to a faction of the rebels' Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front.
   The vice president-elect claimed the Rev. Daniel Sanchez belongs
to the guerrilla faction that was responsible for the bombing of
his home.
   Rivera Damas said the allegations were untrue and Sanchez is
ready ``to prove his innocence before the authorities. He is not
afraid and we reiterate our support for the pastor.''
</TEXT>
