<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico-Teachers 1stLd-Writethru a0728 04-23 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Teachers, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0728,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head of Teachers' Union Resigns</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4 grafs for grafs 10-12, ``Negotiations on ...'' to ADD
background. Pickup 13th graf, ``In the ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of Mexico's most important labor leaders
resigned Sunday as head of the national teachers' union amid a
weeklong strike by dissident union members demanding democratic
reforms.
   A two-paragraph statement from the Presidential Palace said
Carlos Jonguitud Barrios informed President Carlos Salinas de
Gortari that he was resigning as chief of the National Education
Workers' Union. There was no elaboration.
   Earlier Sunday, the dissidents' National Coordinate rejected a
government appeal for tens of thousands of striking teachers to
return to work.
   Instead, the National Coordinate called for a mass rally Monday.
A similar rally last week drew thousands of people to the Zocalo,
Mexico City's central plaza.
   Coordinate leader Teodoro Palomino told the newspaper Excelsior
that the strikers would not return to work until their demands for
democratic reforms within the union are met.
   Dissident teachers went on strike April 17, shutting down
thousands of schools, and their demands included Jonguitud's
resignation and pay increases.
   Jonguitud's handpicked team is still in control of the union,
and it was not clear what effect his resignation might have.
Coordinate leaders were not available for comment.
   The National Education Workers' Union has a membership of more
than 1 million, making it one of the most powerful in Mexico. The
National Coordinate claims it represents about half of the union's
members.
   Previous administrations tried to ignore the dissidents, but the
Salinas administration reacted to the strike by arranging talks
between the union and Coordinate and offered a pay raise of 10
percent. Teachers make an average of about $142 per month.
   It was not clear what Jonguitud's resignation meant to the
strike talks, which had been set to resume Monday after a weekend
recess. The talks have concentrated on the internal union reforms
such as free and open local elections.
   Dissidents say Jonguitud, who has controlled the union since
1972, maintained his power on the organization through fraud and
intimidation and enriched himself while doing virtually nothing to
improve the lot of teachers.
   Jonguitud has denied the charges and said he is not a rich man.
   Jonguitud is closely allied with the governing Institutional
Revolutionary Party. He has been rewarded by the party by being
elected governor of San Luis Potosi state and later to the Senate
from a district dominated by the party.
   In the union he headed a private cadre called the Revolionary
Vanguard and was a permanent adviser to the union's national
advisory council. The presidential statement said he was stepping
down from both of those posts.
</TEXT>
