<FIRST>r i AM-Bulgaria-Greece     04-23 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bulgaria-Greece,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bulgaria and Greece Sign Economic Cooperation Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHASKOVO, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of Greece and Bulgaria on
Sunday signed a 10-year economic cooperation agreement and a
declaration calling for the removal of nuclear and chemical weapons
from the Balkans.
   The pacts were signed by President Todor Zhivkov and Greek
Premier Andreas Papandreou following a one-hour meeting in the
Bulgarian border city of Khaskovo.
   Papandreou said the talks centered on the establishment of a
nuclear-free zone in the Balkans and the joint declaration could
lead to the abolition of all nuclear and chemical weapons in the
area.
   Their declaration called on other regional countries including
Turkey, Romania, Yugooslavia and Albania to sign the agreement.
   Greece is a member of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization and
Bulgaria belongs to the Warsaw Pact alliance.
   Papandreou's plane was escorted by four MiG-23 jet fighters as
it crossed into Bulgarian airspace and then landed at a military
airport outside Khaskovo.
   Papandreou and Zhivkov were greeted by several thousand people
in Khaskovo's main square.
   The economic agreement calls for increasing the number of joint
ventures in the two countries and the transfer of technology.
   Papandreou said a recent decision by Bulgaria to begin
restructuring its economy to allow local companies to negotiate
directly with foreign businesses instead of through the state
machinery would facilitate the establishment of joint ventures.
   The two countries have set up 10 joint ventures under an
agreement signed in 1982.
</TEXT>
