<FIRST>u a AM-BurningSheriff     04-23 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burning Sheriff,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Minister Resigns Rather Than Dismiss ``Mississippi Burning''
Sheriff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MERIDIAN, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black minister resigned Sunday under
criticism for hiring a former sheriff who was charged 25 years ago
in the killings of three civil rights workers depicted in the movie
``Mississippi Burning.''
   The Rev. Evan E. McDonald spoke of God's love and forgiveness in
his last sermon at Golden Grove Missionary Baptist Church before
about 25 parishioners.
   He said he had shown those qualities in hiring former Neshoba
County Sheriff Lawrence Rainey as a guard in his security service
in March 1986.
   Rainey was charged with civil rights violations in the 1964
murders, which were portrayed in fictional form in the movie.
Rainey was acquitted in 1967 of violating their civil rights.
   ``Some of the people real close to me said as long as that man
was working for me there would be no peace in that church. I told
them I'd leave for peace's sake,'' McDonald said prior to the
sermon.
   McDonald, a preacher for 17 years at the church in Meehan,
outside Meridian in eastern Mississippi, said he had received
threatening telephone calls. His security business is ``not
flourishing'' because potential clients are avoiding it, he said.
   ``We teach love. We teach forgiveness. Here are people who
profess to be Christians and they behave like heathens,'' said
McDonald, who planned to preach twice a month at a church in nearby
Alabama.
   Hervy Spinks of Meridian, chairman of Golden Grove's deacons,
wouldn't comment on McDonald's resignation.
   ``That's between him and God,'' he said.
   McDonald said the movie, released in January, had stirred up
racial hostilities, with some of them directed toward him and his
McDonald's Security Service.
   But a local preacher said McDonald had made a mistake in hiring
Rainey.
   ``He was associated with something that's a smear on
Mississippi, a scar on the pages of history,'' said the Rev.
Wardell Tanksley.
   Rainey was among 18 men indicted by a federal grand jury in the
1964 slayings of three civil rights workers, James Chaney, 21;
Andrew Goodman, 20; and Michael Schwerner, 24.
   Church members protested after People magazine published an
article Jan. 9 that made note of Rainey's employment at McDonald's
firm.
   Rainey in February sued Orion Pictures for $8 million, claiming
his reputation was harmed by the portrayal of the sheriff in the
movie.Sheriff Stucky, the film character, is a narrow-minded racist
who helps protect the murderers.
   Some critics have praised the film, directed by Briton Alan
Parker, but activists claim it belittles the role played by blacks
in the civil rights movement.
   Rainey said McDonald had refused his offers to quit the company.
   ``I really hate it for him,'' Rainey said. ``I think it will
finally blow over if they ever quit playing this movie in
Meridian.''
</TEXT>
