<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador-Politics     04-23 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Politics,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>New President of Rightist Party Named</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCOS ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The right-wing Republican
Nationalist Alliance on Sunday named as its new president a close
associate of party founder Roberto D'Aubuisson, who has been linked
to right-wing death squads.
   In an emotional speech, D'Aubuisson nominated Mayor Armando
Calderon Sol, who was elected without opposition. Calderon is a
longtime friend and defender of D'Aubuisson, who has denied
widespead accusations that he sponsored right-wing death squads in
the early 1980s.
   D'Aubuisson, who represents the ultraright of the party known as
Arena, has been described as the group's ``maximum leader.''
   Calderon takes over as party president from the country's
president-elect, Alfredo Cristiani, leader of Arena's more moderate
wing. Calderon and Cristiani, who led the party since September
1985, have not been accused of involvement with death squads.
   Cristiani was elected president on March 19. He takes power from
the Christian Democratic government of President Jose Napoleon
Duarte on June 1.
   ``Arena will not be the classic government party, Arena is
something new, the rebirth of the Salvadoran people,'' Calderon
said. ``Arena will continue being the party that watches over the
government and its officials.''
   Arena has been gaining political power in recent years. It won
the majority of the country's National Assembly and mayoral seats
during 1988 elections.
   Opposition members in recent weeks have charged that repression
in the country has increased considerably since Cristiani's victory.
   On Wednesday and Thursday, army troops and police raided the
offices of a leftist union federation, an organization for refugees
and the homeless and a women's federation. At least 70 people were
arrested.
   Government and police officials said the organizations raided
were fronts for leftist guerrilla groups.
