<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-89 2106EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CollapseAnniversary     04-23 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Collapse Anniversary,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivors Mark Anniversary Of Building Collapse That Killed 28</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn., (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A memorial service marked the second
anniversary of the collapse of the L'Ambiance Plaza on Sunday, the
deadline for claims in the accident that left 28 men dead and
injured 16 others.
   Survivors and relatives signed a $43 million settlement in
December with the 40 companies involved in the project. The
apartment building collapsed while under construction on April 23,
1987.
   Six other workers have filed separate personal-injury claims
since the settlement, said federal Judge Robert C. Zampano. He
would not reveal the nature of the new claims, but he said the
deadline for claims expired Sunday.
   The agreement did not resolve the question of blame, although
investigators said they determined that the method of lift-slab
construction, in which pre-cast concrete floors are hoisted into
place, caused the collapse.
   The Occupational Safety and Health Administration in October
1987 ordered lift-slab companies to make sure their lifting systems
could bear at least 2{ times the expected load.
   Union officials say the agency's new regulations are
insufficient.
   Officials of Texstar Inc., the major lift-slab subcontractor at
L'Ambiance Plaza, still deny the lift-slab system caused the
accident.
   ``There's no question we've gotten a raw deal and full
investigation was not done,'' said Christopher Geckler, president
of the San Antonio, Texas, firm.
   Texstar contributed $3 million to the fund for survivors and
families of the victims, but since has hired a team of engineers
who Geckler says determined the collapse may have been due to a
faulty foundation.
   Federal investigators say Texstar has no evidence to back its
claim.
   Two Connecticut congressmen, Rep. Christopher Shays, a
Republican, and Democratic Sen. Christopher J. Dodd, are working to
develop safety legislation for the construction industry.
   ``Texstar might be bitter, but there were 28 men who lost their
lives and the bottom line is it shouldn't have happened and it
might not have happened if OSHA had been more involved,'' Shays
said.
   Union officials have called for a federal agency to monitor the
construction industry and criminal prosecution of contractors or
project owners involved in fatal accidents.
   Relatives of the victims attended a memorial service Sunday at
St. Augustine Cathedral, not far from the site of the accident.
   Under the settlement, the children of the men who died will
receive a weekly income until they are 30 years old and money for
college if they choose to go. Widows get income from annuities
until they are 62 to 65 years old, when they will be eligible for
Social Security.
</TEXT>
