<FIRST>r a AM-BlackStudies-Protest 1stLd-Writethru a0700 04-23 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Black Studies-Protest, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0700,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Students End Occupation Of Campus Building</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: UPDATES throughout to give details on agreement, students leaving
building. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Africana is cq in 2nd graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM IRWIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of black students at Wayne State
University ended their 1{-week-long occupation of a campus building
Sunday after administrators promised to beef up the black studies
program and minority recruitment.
   The agreement calls for the university to more than double
funding of a newly created Department of Africana Studies, increase
the number of black faculty members and offer at least 10
scholarships to black students.
   The protesters, who have occupied the Helen Newberry Joy Student
Services Center since April 12, began leaving the building Sunday
morning. University officials also agreed not to arrest any of the
students or seek any academic reprisals against them.
   The last round of negotiations ended about 12:30 a.m. Sunday,
and the agreement was signed 45 minutes later, said university
spokesman Vern Foss, who declined any further comment.
   ``I'm happy but I also know that what was done here is not
necessarily the end of what must be done to correct injustices to
members of my race,'' said Walter Boykin, one of the protesters and
a sophomore from Detroit. He said he planned to relax briefly
before studying for upcoming final exams.
   As many as 100 students originally occupied the building, but
only 40 to 50 were there Saturday night and most had left early
Sunday, said a campus police officer who declined to be identified.
   The building houses offices that handle services including
financial aid, registration and student records. It was closed
during the occupation, but was expected to reopen Monday morning.
   The final settlement covered 13 of the students' original 17
demands, Foss said. The four that were dropped during negotiations
included a demand that only Africans or African-Americans teach
courses on Africana, he said.
   The college agreed to create 10 full-time scholarships for black
students, while increasing the number of black faculty members from
the current 99 to 113 within three years.
   The increase would raise the percentage of black Wayne State
faculty members to 8.7 percent, which university officials said was
three times the national average.
   Wayne State is an urban campus with about 30,000 students, 27
percent of whom are black.
   The university also agreed to budget $452,500 for the Department
of Africana Studies in the 1989-90 school year. The Center for
Black Studies, from which the department will be created, received
$163,000 in the 1988-89 budget.
</TEXT>
