<FIRST>r a AM-LouisianaSpill     04-23 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Louisiana Spill,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Waste Water Spill in Grand River Cleaned Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAYOU SORREL, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tanker trucks hauled the last of the
oil-tainted waste water from a leaking barge Sunday and workers
completed the cleanup of the spill in the Grand River.
   ``The environmental damage appears to be minimal,'' said Roger
Davis of GSX Chemical Service.
   The spill occurred Friday when a barge carrying 900,000 gallons
of waste water from an Exxon plant in Houston buckled in the middle
while workers were unloading it.
   Officials said about 10,000 gallons of the non-hazardous
material spilled into the river about 35 miles southwest of Baton
Rouge.
   GSX Land Treatment, a division of the same firm as GSX Chemical,
was being paid to dispose of the waste, said to be 90 percent
water, 7 percent alcohol, and 3 percent oil.
   The barge was to be towed up river to Baton Rouge where any
fumes in the compartments would be removed so it can be inspected,
Davis said.
   He said the simultaneous unloading of tanks on either end of the
barge apparently had caused it to collapse in the middle, rupturing
the remaining tank.
   The spill, which occurred on the edge of a large marshland
called the Atchafalaya Basin, killed some fish, but authorities
said it was quickly contained.
</TEXT>
