<HEAD>Chinese Party Chief Visits North Korea</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zhao Ziyang, general secretary of China's
Communist Party, is making a visit to North Korea that is his first
trip aboard since taking office in November 1987.
   The official Xinhua news agency said Monday that Zhao left
Sunday by special train for Pyongyang, the North Korean capital, on
a goodwill visit.
   It did not say when Zhao would return or give details about his
agenda.
   Zhao began the trip as Chinese university students pressed their
campaign for democratic reforms after a week of rallies in Beijing.
   Xinhua said Zhao is to be the guest of President Kim Il Sung and
was accompanied on the trip by Vice Premier Wu Xueqian.
   China sent in troops to help North Korea during the 1950-53
Korean War. The two communist countries remain close political
allies but in recent years China has pursued growing trade links
with capitalist South Korea.
   China has declared that it has no plans for official ties with
the South Korean government, and Zhao is expected to reassure the
North Koreans that China remains a steadfast ally.
   China publicly supports North Korean proposals for easing
tensions on the divided peninsula and unification proposals. At the
same time it maintains contacts with the United States on how to
avoid violence between the rival Korean governments.
