<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-89 2318EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AlaskaQuakes     04-23 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alaska Quakes,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Moderate Quakes Shake Alaska</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALMER, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two moderate earthquakes far apart shook
Alaska on Sunday, but there were no immediate reports of damage or
injuries, the Alaska Tsunami Warning Center said.
   The first quake was centered 40 miles east of Kobuk, which is
260 miles northwest of Fairbanks, said geophysicist Bill Zitek. The
location was ``somewhat unusual,'' he said.
   Most of the many earthquakes recorded each year in Alaska are
much farther south.
   Zitek gave the preliminary magnitude of the quake as 5.5 on the
Richter scale, a temblor that can cause considerable damage. He
said the 11:21 a.m. quake was felt strongly in Kobuk.
   About six hours later, a 5.0 quake centered about 40 miles west
of Homer rocked the Cook Inlet area and was felt as far away as
Anchorage, 150 miles to the north, spokesman Alec Medbury said.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude.
</TEXT>
