<FIRST>r a AM-Super7Fever     04-23 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Super 7 Fever,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Player Ready For Lottery Lightning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREAT BEND, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gamblers lined up Sunday with dreams of
winning the world's biggest lottery jackpot, but a psychologist
says the chances are nearly 10 million to 1 that many will wind up
with nothing but a bout of depression.
   Tickets were selling at a rate of 750,000 an hour by 5 p.m.
Saturday at the state's 3,312 lottery outlets, according to the
last report from a computer monitoring system, and more than 13
million had been sold since Thursday morning.
   Officials say the Pennsylvania Super 7 jackpot drawing Wednesday
night will be larger than the record-breaking $69.9 million won by
four Illinois ticket-holders April 15.
   ``It's a chance to buy a very large, life-changing prize with a
very small amount of money,'' said Lottery Executive Director James
Scroggins.
   But a psychologist who studies the public appetite for the
lottery warned that many players are in for a major downer when
reality catches up with their dreams.
   ``This lottery fantasy syndrome really heats up when the lotto
jackpot climbs over $50 million,'' said Robert R. Butterworth, a
researcher at Contemporary Psychology Associates Inc. in Los
Angeles. ``People purchase a ticket, ignore the odds and start
thinking of the impossible.''
   Danger signs include spending more than $20 a month on the
lottery, becoming depressed over losses, and sacrificing other
purchases to buy tickets, Butterworth said.
   The odds of winning are calculated at one in 9.6 million per
ticket.
   ``They're out there freezing,'' said Gary Conklin, manager of
Beavers Restaurant in Great Bend, where thousands waited outside in
the northeastern Pennsylvania cold to buy tickets.
   The restaurant called in a police officer to help control the
line that totaled as many as 500 at a time.
   The dreams of the gamblers were as varied as their hometowns and
professions.
   Mary Jo Miles, 32, of Binghamton, N.Y., said she'd pay her
tuition at Yale University. Loretta Chandanais, 21, of Endicott,
N.Y., standing in line with her 8-week-old daughter, said she'd buy
a house and beauty salon.
   ``It's exciting just to see them come in here,'' said Carlene
Haggerty, 40, a waitress at Beavers. ``They all have a dream.
Everybody has a dream.''
   Participants select seven numbers out of 80 in the Super 7
Lottery. The player wins if those seven numbers are among the 11
the state draws.
</TEXT>
